# Git Workflow Rules

## Critical Rule: Never Commit to Main

**ALWAYS create a feature branch before making changes.**

## Workflow Steps

1. **Create Feature Branch**
   ```bash
   git checkout main
   git pull origin main
   git checkout -b feat/feature-name
   ```

2. **Make Changes & Test Locally**
   ```bash
   npm install
   npm run dev          # Test in browser
   npm run build        # Must pass
   npm run preview      # Must work
   ```

3. **Commit When Chunk is Done**
   ```bash
   git status
   git add -A
   git commit -m "feat: descriptive message"
   ```

4. **Push to Feature Branch**
   ```bash
   git push -u origin feat/feature-name
   ```

5. **Create Pull Request**
   - Open PR on GitHub: `feat/feature-name` → `main`
   - Review preview deployment
   - Merge when approved

## Git Hook Protection

A pre-push hook blocks pushing to `main`:
- Location: `.githooks/pre-push`
- Automatically prevents: `git push origin main`
- Allows: Pushing to feature branches

## Branch Naming

- `feat/feature-name` - New features
- `fix/bug-name` - Bug fixes
- `refactor/component-name` - Refactoring
- `docs/update-name` - Documentation

## Testing Requirements

**Before pushing:**
- [ ] `npm run build` passes
- [ ] `npm run preview` works
- [ ] No console errors
- [ ] Tested on mobile/tablet/desktop
- [ ] README updated (if needed)

## Never Do This

❌ `git checkout main` then make changes
❌ `git commit` on main branch
❌ `git push origin main` directly
❌ Skip local testing
❌ Push broken builds

## Always Do This

✅ Create feature branch first
✅ Test locally before committing
✅ Run `npm run build` before pushing
✅ Push to feature branch only
✅ Create PR for review
✅ Merge via PR when approved
